# Project Context

## Purpose
VS Code extension that adds a PM2 process tree to the Explorer panel with start/stop/restart/logs actions and optimistic UI updates.

## Scope
Extension UI and command handling only. Does not manage pm2 configuration, ecosystem files, or deployment. Calls pm2 CLI as an external binary, no pm2 Node.js API dependency.

## Key Principles
1. No runtime dependencies, only devDependencies; bundled via tsc, not webpack/esbuild.
2. `extensionKind: ["ui"]` — local use only, not Remote SSH.
3. Optimistic updates: show status change immediately, poll pm2 to confirm, abort on error.
4. All pm2 interaction via `execFileAsync('pm2', [...])`, never shell string interpolation.
5. All pm2 CLI actions target processes by `pm_id` (numeric id), never by name — names are not unique.
6. Tree items are stateless value objects; all state lives in `Pm2Provider`.
7. TypeScript strict mode; no unsafe casts, validate external data before typing.
8. `status: Pm2Status | string` — known statuses map to enum, unknown pm2 statuses pass through as-is.

## Structure
- `src/`: extension source
- `tests/`: vitest unit tests; vscode mocked via vi.mock (no vscode runtime needed)

## File Responsibilities
Each file has a single responsibility. Never mix them: no functions in constants, no constants in utils, no logic in types or enums.
- `constants.ts`: constants and lookup structures only
- `utils.ts`: pure utility functions
- `types.ts`: interfaces and type aliases
- `enums.ts`: enums

## Workflow with AI
- Prefer editing existing files; the codebase is intentionally small, avoid adding abstractions.
- When touching pm2-provider.ts polling logic, watch for concurrent polls and abort flags.
- `package.json` `contributes.menus` controls which buttons appear per contextValue; keep in sync with Pm2Item switch cases.
- No new runtime dependencies without explicit discussion.
